Teagan Air
My flight logbook has been officially activated now. I have a record of 2.3 hours of flight time.
Teagan Air
If I had to describe what it's like to fly a small plane, I would say it's like driving a motorcycle/ATV at 4,000 feet.
In the terrain, the situation changes rapidly. The terrain has a certain degree of instability, so a motorcycle or 4WD is needed.
Moreover, you may not know that when driving an airplane on the ground, it's controlled by the feet, not the control yoke. The rudder pedals and brakes are used for this. It's not a car.
When flying in the air, you will feel bumps and oscillations, feeling like sailing on the water. Although you can control the aircraft, sometimes the airflow will make you a bit dizzy, so you need to adapt to flying in the air, just like a sailor adapts to sailing.
About this, there's also a random little anecdote:
Flying is very tiring.  Today, my back and legs are very sore, feeling like I've been to the gym to exercise.
It's not as simple as driving around on a Sunday. To a novice like me, it's more like a sport than a cruise.
Dear friends, have a great weekend. Welcome to 4000 feet in the sky.
Tomorrow I will fly again, and we will practice stalling and slow flight.
Today's weather isn't very stable, but it's extremely interesting. We practiced slow flight and stalls. Our ground speed once dropped to 16 miles per hour, while our airspeed was still 65 miles per hour.
The weather is fine today, although there's a bit of haze in the high sky, the view is still great.
